<subSubSection id="E25B94643CDB75F08A710016601679E8" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="00CA3E5225B103F350D5163218A92432" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2FE10C9981A7EF25A456002A1D4264BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">The specific name is derived from the type locality, Lingxiufeng Scenic Spot; adjective.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65F2CE78B031EE1CFB9F56EFC8D85FB1" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="419A4CB742716B1017C0D9962BC134F8" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="418B01605ACB80E2EA4A3DC6CBF83592" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
The female of 
<taxonomicName id="D2CE12F120836A9EAE033886C80DD0D4" genus="P." lsidName="P. lingxiufengica" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="lingxiufengica">
<emphasis id="1694BDCE866D37DA81D3B8C0FCAC0130" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">P. lingxiufengica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="085BBF869BF627DA59D6B5550E2EF242" genus="P." lsidName="P. tangi" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="tangi">
<emphasis id="785FC81CB803252280D09FFB75F3B754" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">P. tangi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wang, Mi &amp; Peng, 2016 in having well-developed transverse ridge of copulatory openings (
<emphasis id="8D979CAE7F3543142ED7EE3D28986FFD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">TrR</emphasis>
) (= atrial intermediate margin of 
<bibRefCitation id="CFAF6B24A9E9C3DC4FA4D283AF7B2C35" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2016.1197163" author="Wang, C" journalOrPublisher="Oriental Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" pagination="129 - 134" refId="B23" refString="Wang, C, Mi, XQ, Peng, XJ, 2016. A new species of Pharta Thorell, 1891 (Araneae: Thomisidae) from China. Oriental Insects 50 (3): 129 - 134, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2016.1197163" title="A new species of Pharta Thorell, 1891 (Araneae: Thomisidae) from China." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2016.1197163" volume="50" year="2016">Wang et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
) and invisible copulatory openings (
<emphasis id="C416E4AF9E351273C30F72EC2D687EFB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">CO</emphasis>
). The new species can be easily differentiated from 
<taxonomicName id="FB8F05FF543950CD2F51630EDED367FA" genus="P." lsidName="P. tangi" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="tangi">
<emphasis id="10081168FBBFF8DF84CE28E93CEE45FA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">P. tangi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the convex transverse ridge of copulatory openings (vs. concave) (cf. Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5A724DDAD3EC441C2B90C4CCDAEC43B2" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Pharta lingxiufengica sp. nov., female holotype. A habitus, dorsal view B same, ventral view C epigyne, ventral view D same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, SP - spermatheca, TrR - transverse ridge of copulatory openings. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, B), 0.1 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672173" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">11C</figureCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="9E97F6AEAD869BD363AAE793578A981E" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2016.1197163" author="Wang, C" journalOrPublisher="Oriental Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" pagination="129 - 134" refId="B23" refString="Wang, C, Mi, XQ, Peng, XJ, 2016. A new species of Pharta Thorell, 1891 (Araneae: Thomisidae) from China. Oriental Insects 50 (3): 129 - 134, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2016.1197163" title="A new species of Pharta Thorell, 1891 (Araneae: Thomisidae) from China." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2016.1197163" volume="50" year="2016">Wang et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 2C).
</paragraph>
<caption id="498A2814D7ED538193BB87133886ECF3" doi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672173" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" start="Figure 11" startId="F11">
<paragraph id="CD6CB49D329408CAA9974BC6AE55D6B1" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="6969863E3481E044278ECD38CD258879" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Figure 11.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4D3C5F00EA025F33B52A878591BBAEAA" authorityName="Liu" authorityYear="2022" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Pharta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pharta lingxiufengica" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lingxiufengica">
<emphasis id="7D00CD62BFA35886CC6EF609F13EEA4B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Pharta lingxiufengica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., female holotype. 
<emphasis id="631E8D9B8DFB7784A36E463DB602BB7A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">A</emphasis>
habitus, dorsal view 
<emphasis id="DD2100B56E8483AFF95B41680B62739D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">B</emphasis>
same, ventral view 
<emphasis id="862452C89319FD522B59459823BA21E8" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">C</emphasis>
epigyne, ventral view 
<emphasis id="D07ADC23720A954B8B0180890D3A0A4F" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">D</emphasis>
same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, SP - spermatheca, TrR - transverse ridge of copulatory openings. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (
<emphasis id="A8498D90CCAC78172EE33F0B48672AC7" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">A, B</emphasis>
), 0.1 mm (
<emphasis id="BFFAACEFB8DE42A8AC56AF511B0F357E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">C, D</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="97DC737D03CAF92D0C60B7DB7399AC08" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="description">
<paragraph id="A763FF150D4901AB0869D018DF301217" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9CDE1909135EB79DCD8EACD33174B579" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Habitus as in Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BE974E7485B5E901BFC2E008E0A2B877" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Pharta lingxiufengica sp. nov., female holotype. A habitus, dorsal view B same, ventral view C epigyne, ventral view D same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, SP - spermatheca, TrR - transverse ridge of copulatory openings. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, B), 0.1 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672173" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">11A, B</figureCitation>
. Total length 3.08. Carapace: 3.67 long, 3.33 wide. Eye sizes and interdistances: AME 0.05, ALE 0.15, PME 0.10, PLE 0.14, AME-AME 0.07, AME-ALE 0.04, PME-PME 0.12, PME-PLE 0.13, AME-PME 0.22, AME-PLE 0.31, ALE-ALE 0.25, PLE-PLE 0.57, ALE-PLE 0.14. MOA 0.35 long, front width 0.18, back width 0.32. Chelicerae with three promarginal (proximal largest, distal smallest) and three retromarginal (middle and distal with a same base, distal largest, middle smallest) teeth. Endites slightly longer than wide, anterior part broad. Labium slightly wider than long. Sternum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="16A8B714612A7071F81140BFC56FE2D3" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Pharta lingxiufengica sp. nov., female holotype. A habitus, dorsal view B same, ventral view C epigyne, ventral view D same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, SP - spermatheca, TrR - transverse ridge of copulatory openings. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, B), 0.1 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672173" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">11B</figureCitation>
) with numerous setae, anteromedially procurved, with subtriangular posterior end. Abdomen (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="38FA9110C3AC2B4B83B70CFDE1FA3CF6" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Pharta lingxiufengica sp. nov., female holotype. A habitus, dorsal view B same, ventral view C epigyne, ventral view D same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, SP - spermatheca, TrR - transverse ridge of copulatory openings. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, B), 0.1 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672173" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">11A, B</figureCitation>
): 1.69 long, 1.63 wide, with sparse, erected setae. Leg measurements: I 4.28 (1.35, 0.51, 1.22, 0.87, 0.33); II 4.09 (1.23, 0.48, 1.18, 0.80, 0.40); III 2.31 (0.73, 0.36, 0.59, 0.38, 0.25); IV 2.71 (0.93, 0.33, 0.64, 0.55, 0.26). Leg spination: I Fe: d4, p2; Pa: d2; Ti: d2, v10; Mt: v8; II Fe: d1; Pa: d2; Ti: d2, v10; Mt: v8; III Fe: d3; Pa: d1; Ti: d2, p2, v2; Mt: d2, v2; IV: Fe: d1; Pa: d1, r1; Ti: d3, p1, r1; Mt: d2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2144893AE110BDF5BBDA3CF50F93A00D" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Colouration (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DCF620B141A7F3BD68206BFFF7433532" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Pharta lingxiufengica sp. nov., female holotype. A habitus, dorsal view B same, ventral view C epigyne, ventral view D same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, SP - spermatheca, TrR - transverse ridge of copulatory openings. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, B), 0.1 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672173" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">11A, B</figureCitation>
). Carapace yellow-brown, medially with single broad, dark brown, mottled band. Legs yellow, basis of macrosetae on legs appearing as darkish brown dots. Chelicerae, endites, sternum, legs, and abdomen reddish yellow. Abdomen with sparse white guanine spots, medially with clear inverted T-shaped dark brown marking; macrosetal bases reddish brown; venter with pairs of longitudinal, short, guanine stripes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="736121F5BBA20AF4C06A1100854454D4" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Epigyne (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C4A080CFE89EE931CC6F7D501BE75701" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Pharta lingxiufengica sp. nov., female holotype. A habitus, dorsal view B same, ventral view C epigyne, ventral view D same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: CO - copulatory opening, FD - fertilisation duct, SP - spermatheca, TrR - transverse ridge of copulatory openings. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, B), 0.1 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672173" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">11C, D</figureCitation>
). Epigyne oval, 1.5 
<normalizedToken id="D96731F3BA7A08FD04EFCA7548B84EEE" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
wider than long, lacking hood. Copulatory openings (
<emphasis id="E5ED5199F0ED06E412003E4B2687AC41" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">CO</emphasis>
) invisible, hidden by transverse ridge of copulatory openings (
<emphasis id="D888BDD66658DCACFD2F0B0851960624" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">TrR</emphasis>
). Copulatory ducts (
<emphasis id="5650FD1D9091C007EFA65CF498D26DBD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">CD</emphasis>
) not visible, possibly absent. Spermathecae (
<emphasis id="D5A762BEFD80685F6EE32F4A913BE59F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">SP</emphasis>
) oval, ~ 1.4 
<normalizedToken id="7C7AEB6D918FC2B2E27D35AD99250EFF" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide, anterior part of spermathecae slightly separated, posterior parts touching. Fertilisation ducts (
<emphasis id="D45581BD601BC8827B2626A3D05C9C1C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">FD</emphasis>
) as long as width of spermatheca, directed laterally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EF7541F2C8858410B34C8F0E16ECC1D6" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="4CA98271089D0B658BE03480F0F4CFEC" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Male.</emphasis>
unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5F1B8E92A83354048A14167AD1E3684E" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="comments">
<paragraph id="21093C33249136A625845D384F5801F9" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="70D903085718B74EADD7C3D201784230" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
There is only one species in the region known from the male only, 
<taxonomicName id="E07E11E75AAB5AA33E984DFF4822C672" genus="P." lsidName="P. koponeni" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="koponeni">
<emphasis id="5F0FBE1EC701DF1853B4E015BC183AFC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">P. koponeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Benjamin, 2014 (Thailand); however, it is unlikely to be conspecific with our female because of differences in colouration, and the long distance between type localities.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="111724F1C9E5D267F3E242A7B9B47F48" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="138AF7D32B85903C3676FFC4C8486A1A" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="29D5B549C129DBFDB5E4AB09F1B78604" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Known only from the type locality in Jiangxi Province of China (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="24E119A6C9578B7A8603D115C980F00F" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. The location of the Jinggang Mountain National Nature Reserve in China indicated by a large black dot." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.72829.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672179" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">17</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
